        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Not to beat a dead horse, but - to me - advertising is any statement made to the public with the intention of promoting the purchase of a particular product.  It is pretty easy to argue that an inverview with a gaming magazine, or an official statement on their webpage is an advertisement, since these are meant to entice you to buy them.</P><P>Now, to the real issue at hand.  I am not taking any of the information posted as fact.  Frankly, I doubt they could have levelled up and tested those spells properly in the short time they were 'accidentally' out on Test.</P><P>I suspect the leak was intentional.  The fact that most of the information was for necros and mages tells me that they know they have some butts to kiss with these two classes.  that alone is encouraging.  I am not getting my hopes up, but it seems like a hint of a step in the right direction.  Of course, we have no idea what the clerics and enchanters will see - excluding of course the all int caster spells.</P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
